2893 In Rural Press Ltd v Australian Competition and Consumer Commission [2003] HCA 75 ; (2003) 216 CLR 53, the joint judgment of Gummow, Hayne and Heydon JJ held that:


 • the statutory concept of a particular class of persons is not limited to competitors of the parties to the relevant contract or arrangement (at 81 [63]);
 • a provision may have the purpose of limiting the acquisition of goods and services from a particular class of persons even though the identity of all members of the class may not be ascertainable (at 90 [87]);
 • it is not necessary in order for s 4D to apply that the provision be ' aimed at ' a class of persons, nor that it inflict damage or harm on the class (at 83-84 [70]), following News Ltd v South Sydney District Rugby League Football Club Ltd [2003] HCA 45 ; (2003) 215 CLR 563, at 590-591 [76]-[79], per Gummow J; and
 • it is preferable to speak of a provision being ' directed toward ' a particular class, rather than being ' aimed at ' the class (at 84 [70]).

